	<li class="comment byuser comment-author-admin bypostauthor even depth-2" id="comment-4262" >
		<div class="c-grav"><img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/e5cbb32cf54a237e409a3608fc2f88d1?s=40&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F0.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D40&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-40 photo' height='40' width='40' /></div>
		<div class="c-body">
			<div class="c-head">
				Michael Nielsen <span class="c-permalink"><a href="http://www.michaelnielsen.org/ddi/how-the-bitcoin-protocol-actually-works/#comment-4262">permalink</a></span>
			</div>
						<p>On incentive: such could be built into the protocol.</p>
<p>On trusting the answers: if someone claims that they see evidence of double spending, you&#8217;d require them to present evidence in the form of a signed transaction.  The requirement of a signature makes this hard to forge by a malicious naysayer.</p>
<p>On your last point, yes, this is a very interesting question.  At present this all seems to be working okay, but over the long run I suspect will limit the use of Bitcoin for small transactions.</p>
						<div class="reply">
							</div>
