	<ul class="children">
	<li class="comment byuser comment-author-admin bypostauthor odd alt depth-2" id="comment-4331" >
		<div class="c-grav"><img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/e5cbb32cf54a237e409a3608fc2f88d1?s=40&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F0.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D40&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-40 photo' height='40' width='40' /></div>
		<div class="c-body">
			<div class="c-head">
				Michael Nielsen <span class="c-permalink"><a href="http://www.michaelnielsen.org/ddi/how-the-bitcoin-protocol-actually-works/#comment-4331">permalink</a></span>
			</div>
						<p>In practice, there are thin clients which don&#8217;t keep a full copy of the block chain.  But the way the protocol is designed at present there is a sizeable number of people keeping a full copy of the block chain.  This is currently quite a manageable size (about 12 gig).  If Bitcoin grows rapidly enough this may eventually become a problem.  There&#8217;s a nice discussion of this and related scalability issues here:</p>
<p><a href="https://en.bitcoin.it/wiki/Scalability" rel="nofollow">https://en.bitcoin.it/wiki/Scalability</a></p>
<p>The conclusion there, which seems to me believable, is that there are many options for scaling Bitcoin at least up to the level at which credit cards are used today, and perhaps further.</p>
						<div class="reply">
							</div>
					</div><!--end c-body-->
