	<ul class="children">
	<li class="comment byuser comment-author-admin bypostauthor even depth-2" id="comment-4393" >
		<div class="c-grav"><img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/e5cbb32cf54a237e409a3608fc2f88d1?s=40&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F0.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D40&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-40 photo' height='40' width='40' /></div>
		<div class="c-body">
			<div class="c-head">
				Michael Nielsen <span class="c-permalink"><a href="http://www.michaelnielsen.org/ddi/how-the-bitcoin-protocol-actually-works/#comment-4393">permalink</a></span>
			</div>
						<p>I&#8217;ve wondered the same thing.  Some observations: if you copy someone&#8217;s private key, and then erase their copy, there is no way for them to prove that it was ever truly their key.  And if two people both have a copy of the private key, how do you determine who &#8220;truly&#8221; owns it?</p>
<p>The situation is complicated further by the possibility of laundering.  If you quickly spend some stolen bitcoins on, then it becomes very different to later recover those bitcoins, since now they may be in possession of honest parties.</p>
						<div class="reply">
							</div>
