	<ul class="children">
	<li class="comment byuser comment-author-admin bypostauthor odd alt depth-2" id="comment-4487" >
		<div class="c-grav"><img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/e5cbb32cf54a237e409a3608fc2f88d1?s=40&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F0.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D40&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-40 photo' height='40' width='40' /></div>
		<div class="c-body">
			<div class="c-head">
				Michael Nielsen <span class="c-permalink"><a href="http://www.michaelnielsen.org/ddi/how-the-bitcoin-protocol-actually-works/#comment-4487">permalink</a></span>
			</div>
						<p>The transaction contains the Bitcoin address of the payee (or payees, if there are multiple outputs) in the output fields, and the public key(s) and signature(s) of the payer(s) in the input fields.  So there&#8217;s no problem &#8212; you do have the full public key of the payer.</p>
